<subsection xml:id="C26.S7.SS2">
<title>Generating Function</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C26.S7.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="53" xml:id="C26.S7.SS2.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="26.7.5" mode="display" xml:id="C26.S7.E5">\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}B\left(n\right)\frac{x^{n}}{n!}=\exp({\mathrm{e}^{x}}-1)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C26.S7.SS3">
<title>Recurrence Relation</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C26.S7.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="54" xml:id="C26.S7.SS3.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="26.7.6" mode="display" xml:id="C26.S7.E6">B\left(n+1\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\genfrac{(}{)}{0.0pt}{}{n}{k}B\left(k\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C26.S7.SS4">
<title>Asymptotic Approximation</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="55" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="26.7.7" mode="display" xml:id="C26.S7.E7">B\left(n\right)=\frac{N^{n}{\mathrm{e}^{N-n-1}}}{(1+\ln N)^{1/2}}\left(1+O \left(\frac{(\ln n)^{1/2}}{n^{1/2}}\right)\right), if n\to\infty,</Math> where <Math equation-number="26.7.8" mode="display" xml:id="C26.S7.E8">N\ln N=n,</Math> or, equivalently, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.m1">N={\mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{Wm}\left(n\right)}}</Math> , with properties of the Lambert function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.m2">\mathrm{Wm}\left(n\right)</Math> given in §4.13.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="56" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.s2">
For higher approximations to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.m3">B\left(n\right)</Math> as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C26.S7.SS4.p1.m4">n\to\infty</Math> see de Bruijn (1961, pp. 104–108).
</sentence>

</para>

 
